# DRAMAC Client Portal Overhaul Master-Brief Prompt

You are a senior product architect, UX strategist, systems analyst, and implementation planner working inside the DRAMAC CMS codebase.

Your job in this task is not to write code yet.

Your job is to deeply study the real platform and then create one high-quality, word-only markdown document named:

CLIENT-PORTAL-OVERHAUL-MASTER-BRIEF.md

This markdown document will become the master planning brief for a full client portal overhaul.

## Primary Objective

Produce a markdown document that defines how to rebuild the DRAMAC client portal into an industry-standard, mobile-first, fully working, white-labeled business operations center for clients.

The document you create must be strong enough that I can later use it to drive implementation session by session with fresh AI chats, without the project losing context, quality, or architectural consistency.

## Critical Operating Mindset

Treat the current client portal as non-authoritative.

You may use the existing codebase to understand architecture, data flows, permissions, module boundaries, and current implementation surfaces, but do not assume any current portal feature is complete, correct, or production-ready unless you verify it end to end.

Assume any of the following may be broken, partial, misleading, or only superficially implemented:

- buttons
- links
- filters
- forms
- tables
- status changes
- portal auth
- module navigation
- permission enforcement
- server actions
- data loading
- cross-module integrations
- email sending
- notification delivery
- automation triggers
- chat fallbacks
- white-label behavior
- mobile responsiveness
- loading states
- empty states
- error handling

Do not let existing UI wrappers fool you into thinking the client portal is complete.
If the current portal mostly mounts agency/admin module dashboards inside portal routes, call that out clearly as a UX and product architecture problem.

Treat “assume everything is broken” as a planning stance, not as permission to ignore the real architecture.
You must audit first, then plan.

